male":"1271–Afdød","1240–Male":"1240–Afdød","1287–Male":"1287–Afdød","1250–Male":"1250–Afdød","about 1271":"omkring 1271","1315":"1315","1287":"1287","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","about 1287":"omkring 1287","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Merton, Devon, England":"Merton, Devon, England"},"nl":{"about 1271–":"circa 1271–Overleden","1271–Female":"1271–Overleden","1240–Male":"1240–Overleden","1287–Male":"1287–Overleden","1250–Male":"1250–Overleden","about 1271":"circa 1271","1315":"1315","1287":"1287","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","about 1287":"circa 1287","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Merton, Devon, England":"Merton, Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1271–":"about 1271–Deceased","1271–Female":"1271–Deceased","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1287–Male":"1287–Deceased","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","about 1271":"about 1271","1315":"1315","1287":"1287","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","about 1287":"about 1287","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Merton, Devon, England":"Merton, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Purcell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Welsh, and Irish (of Norman origin): from Old French <i>pourcel</i> ‘little pig’ (from Latin <i>porcellus</i>, a diminutive of <i>porcus</i> ‘pig’), hence a metonymic occupational name for a swineherd, or a nickname, perhaps denoting someone thought to resemble a pig. This surname is common in Ireland, having become established there in the 12th century. There may sometimes be confusion with   Pearsall  .","English: habitational name from Purshull in Elmbridge, Worcestershire. The placename derives from an uncertain first element + Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’."],"variants":[{"name":"Pearsall","meanings":["English (West Midlands):","habitational name from Pearshall in Staffordshire. The placename probably derives from Old English <i>pise</i>, <i>peosu</i> ‘pea’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’.","occasionally a variant of   Purcell  ."]},{"name":"Parcells","meanings":["English and Welsh: variant of   Purcell  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Parcel","meanings":["English (Surrey) and Welsh (Glamorgan): variant of   Purcell  ."]},{"name":"Parsell","meanings":["English: variant of   Purcell  ."]},{"name":"Parsells","meanings":["English: variant of   Purcell  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Persell","meanings":["English: variant of   Purcell  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Procell","meanings":["Probably an altered (metathesized) form of   Purcell  ."]},{"name":"Pursell","meanings":["English: variant of   Purcell  .","Americanized form of German <b>Burschel</b> or <b>Bürschel</b>, diminutives of   Bursch  ."]},{"name":"Parcell","meanings":["English and Welsh: variant of   Purcell  ."]},{"name":"Percell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Purcell  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."]}]},{"name":"Joyce","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":19,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":44,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":57,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joyce Purcell was born about 1271, in Merton, Devon, England as the daughter of William Purcell. She had at least 1 son with Owen de Mutton."},"et":{"about 1271–":"umbes 1271–Surnud","1271–Female":"1271–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","about 1271":"umbes 1271","1315":"1315","1287":"1287","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","about 1287":"umbes 1287","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Merton, Devon, England":"Merton, Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1271–":"noin 1271–Kuollut","1271–Female":"1271–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1287–Male":"1287